   849	The self-validation scenario is the closest thing to a proof that the
   850	suite asserts what it claims. Chapter 09 §3 leans on this scenario
   851	when it says "every assertion in the suite is keyed off a normative
   852	MUST." The meta is the integrity check that connects the assertion
   853	text to a concrete observable failure.
   854	
   855	### G. Spec chapter 09
   856	
   857	Chapter 09 is short by design. The chapter's job is to declare the
   858	relationship between the spec, the suite, and any IUT — not to
   859	duplicate content from chapters 02 / 04 / 05 / 06 / 07 / 08.
   860	
   861	```markdown
   862	# Conformance
   863	
   864	This chapter declares what conformance to EDEN protocol v0 means and
   865	how it is verified.
   866	
   867	## 1. What conformance is
   868	
   869	A v0-conforming IUT (implementation under test) implements chapter
   870	07's HTTP wire binding with the normative semantics of chapters 02 /
   871	03 / 04 / 05 / 06 / 08.
   872	
   873	Conformance is verified by passing the conformance suite under
   874	[`conformance/`](../../conformance/) in this repo: a set of black-box
   875	scenarios that drive an IUT through chapter-07 HTTP and assert MUSTs
   876	from those chapters. The suite is delivered in three increments —
   877	**v1**, **v1+roles**, and **v1+roles+integrator** — each adding a
   878	group of scenarios to the prior level. **An IUT MUST qualify its
   879	conformance claim with the level it passes** (e.g. "v1 conformant",
   880	"v1+roles+integrator conformant"); the term "v0 conformance" without
   881	a level qualifier is reserved for the final `v1+roles+integrator`
   882	level once it exists. Until then, an unqualified "v0 conformance"
   883	claim is not meaningful.
   884	
   885	The suite is one expression, not the only one. A future suite — in a
   886	different language, against a different harness — that drives the same
   887	chapter-07 endpoints and asserts the same MUSTs would be equally
   888	authoritative. The spec is the source of truth; the suite is one
   889	faithful implementation of "what would test that?"
   890	
   891	## 2. The IUT
   892	
   893	An IUT MUST:
   894	
   895	- Expose chapter 07's HTTP binding at a deployment-chosen base URL.
   896	- Accept an experiment configuration whose shape matches
   897	  `experiment-config.schema.json`.
   898	
   899	Anything else — language, deployment topology, persistence, auth
   900	scheme, scaling profile — is a deployment choice. Chapter 07 §11
   901	enumerates further latitude.
   902	
   903	## 3. Assertion vocabulary
   904	
   905	Every assertion in the v1 suite is keyed off a normative MUST in
   906	chapters 02 / 04 / 05 / 06 / 07 / 08. The suite does NOT assert
   907	SHOULDs; SHOULDs are interop guidance, not interop contracts.
   908	
   909	When the spec evolves, the suite evolves with it. A change that
   910	removes a MUST or downgrades it to SHOULD MUST be accompanied by a
   911	matching scenario removal or rewrite.
   912	
   913	The suite intentionally does NOT certify §1.3-class atomicity or §3.2
   914	unforgeability properties; black-box testing cannot prove the absence
   915	of a sufficiently-narrow window or the absence of a sufficiently-weak
   916	random source. The v1 suite asserts the testable consequences of these
   917	invariants (event presence, uniqueness across observed claims) and
   918	labels the regression-style tests as such.
   919	
   920	## 4. Conformance levels
   921	
   922	The v0 spec defines exactly one wire binding (chapter 07 HTTP). The
   923	suite drives every IUT through it; transport-neutral semantic tests
   924	vs. per-binding wire tests cannot be meaningfully separated until a
   925	second binding exists. Levels are therefore distinguished by
   926	**scenario coverage**, not transport:
   927	
   928	- **v1** — task-store and event-log MUSTs from chapters 02 / 04 /
   929	  05 / 07 plus the chapter-08 storage MUSTs the wire binding exposes
   930	  (§1.1, §1.7). v1 does NOT cover chapter-03 role contracts or the
   931	  chapter-06 integrator atomicity ladder.
   932	
   933	- **v1+roles** — adds chapter-03 role-contract scenarios (per-role
   934	  submission semantics, backpressure, idempotency). Lands in chunk
   935	  11c.
   936	
   937	- **v1+roles+integrator** — adds chapter-06 integrator scenarios
   938	  (squash shape, eval-manifest shape, `work/*` access discipline,
   939	  the §3.4 atomicity ladder under transport-indeterminate failures).
   940	  Lands in chunk 11d.
   941	
   942	A future spec lineage that introduces a second wire binding will at
   943	that point split the suite into transport-neutral semantic tests +
   944	per-binding wire tests, and chapter 09 will gain a `core` level
   945	claimable by IUTs implementing only the semantic layer. The marker
   946	structure in [`conformance/`](../../conformance/) anticipates that
   947	refactor but does not enable it in v0.
   948	
   949	## 5. Scenario index (v1; v1+roles and v1+roles+integrator extend)
   950	
   951	| Group | Scope | Spec citations |
   952	|---|---|---|
   953	| Task lifecycle | Every legal/illegal transition. | 04 §1, §3, §4 |
   954	| Claim tokens | Freshness, authorization, no-reclaim-while-claimed. | 04 §3 |
   955	| Submit idempotency | Content-equivalent / divergent / post-terminal. | 04 §4.2, §4.4 |
   956	| Reclamation | Case matrix; token invalidation; trial reconciliation. | 04 §5 |
   957	| Atomicity (regression test) | State + event consistency around a transition. Best-effort, not a certification. | 04 §1.3 |
   958	| Event envelope | Chapter-05 §1 envelope shape; uniqueness. | 05 §1, §1.1 |
   959	| Per-type event payloads | Each registered type's required fields. | 05 §3 |
   960	| Composite commits | Implement-dispatch, implement-terminal, evaluate-terminal cases, implement-reclaim-with-starting-trial. | 05 §2.2 |
   961	| Event delivery | Total order, replay from cursor 0, at-least-once, long-poll subscribe. | 05 §4; 07 §6.2 |
   962	| Status codes | Each operation's spec-pinned status. | 07 §§2-6 |
   963	| Problem+json envelope | Shape + content-type. | 07 §7 |
   964	| Error vocabulary closure | Closed `eden://error/<name>` set; observed exhaustively. | 07 §7 |
   965	| Experiment-id header disagreement | 400 experiment-id-mismatch. | 07 §1.3 |
   966	| Integrate idempotency | Same-value / different-value / preconditions. | 07 §5 |
   967	
   968	Chunk 11c adds the v1+roles entries (chapter 03 role contracts);
   969	chunk 11d adds the v1+roles+integrator entries (chapter 06 integrator
   970	flows). The exact scenario lists for those levels are out of scope
   971	for the v1 chapter-09 ship; they will be appended in their respective
   972	chunks.
   973	
   974	## 6. Adapter (informative)
   975	
   976	A v1 IUT does NOT need to ship a Python adapter. The reference suite's
   977	adapter shape — under
   978	[`conformance/harness/adapter.py`](../../conformance/harness/adapter.py)
   979	— is one convenience for IUTs that prefer to integrate with the
   980	reference Python harness; it is not a normative requirement. A non-
   981	Python implementor MAY:
   982	
   983	- Write a Python `IutAdapter` subclass that spawns their service.
   984	- Run the suite against an already-running IUT pointed at by an
   985	  environment variable, via a thin Python adapter that simply

